      "post_id" : 5322730,
      "comment_id" : 124197090,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "I agree with the advice for practical reasons (having a different name for the variable and getter), but not the reasoning. <i>Is</i> and <i>has</i> are stative verbs, and are fine to use for naming boolean properties. It&#39;s active verbs specifically that should be reserved for functions."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 1665095,
        "reputation" : 576,
        "user_id" : 1532672,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d831264327d63f3c1994bca5104b2302?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Christian Vermeulen",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1532672/christian-vermeulen"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1728981159,
      "post_id" : 5322730,
      "comment_id" : 139455827,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "<code>Is is a verb and verbs are inappropriate to represent an Object&#39;s state</code> I disagree with this. <code>current</code> is ambigious as it can also mean the flow of water (in m/s?) or an electrical current (v or a). By including the verb you make it clear this is a boolean state property."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 138128,
      "reputation" : 300582,
      "user_id" : 342852,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 97,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/aLKQa.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Sean Patrick Floyd",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/342852/sean-patrick-floyd"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 89,
    "last_activity_date" : 1300264527,
    "creation_date" : 1300264527,
    "answer_id" : 5322730,
    "question_id" : 5322648,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>For a field named <code>isCurrent</code>, the correct getter / setter naming is <code>setCurrent()</code> / <code>isCurrent()</code> (at least that's what Eclipse thinks), which is highly confusing and can be traced back to the main problem:</p>\n\n<p><strong>Your field should not be called <code>isCurrent</code> in the first place.</strong> <em>Is</em> is a verb and verbs are inappropriate to represent an Object's state. Use an adjective instead, and suddenly your getter / setter names will make more sense:</p>\n\n<pre><code>private boolean current;\n\npublic boolean isCurrent(){\n    return current;\n}\n\npublic void setCurrent(final boolean current){\n    this.current = current;\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
