    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 6,
    "last_activity_date" : 1478603801,
    "creation_date" : 1478603801,
    "answer_id" : 40485512,
    "question_id" : 5322648,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Maybe it is time to start revising this answer? Personally I would vote for <code>setActive()</code> and <code>unsetActive()</code> (alternatives can be <code>setUnActive()</code>, <code>notActive()</code>, <code>disable()</code>, etc. depending on context) since \"setActive\" implies you activate it at all times, which you don't. It's kind of counter intuitive to say \"setActive\" but actually remove the active state.</p>\n\n<p>Another problem is, you can can not listen to specifically a SetActive event in a CQRS way, you would need to listen to a 'setActiveEvent' and determine inside that listener wether is was actually set active or not. Or of course determine which event to call when calling <code>setActive()</code> but that then goes against the Separation of Concerns principle.</p>\n\n<p>A good read on this is the FlagArgument article by Martin Fowler: <a href=\"http://martinfowler.com/bliki/FlagArgument.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://martinfowler.com/bliki/FlagArgument.html</a></p>\n\n<p>However, I come from a PHP background and see this trend being adopted more and more. Not sure how much this lives with Java development.</p>\n"
  }, {
