    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : -6,
    "last_activity_date" : 1534407338,
    "creation_date" : 1534407338,
    "answer_id" : 51872523,
    "question_id" : 5322648,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>As a setter, how about:</p>\n\n<pre><code>// setter\npublic void beCurrent(boolean X) {\n    this.isCurrent = X;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>or</p>\n\n<pre><code>// setter\npublic void makeCurrent(boolean X) {\n    this.isCurrent = X;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>I'm not sure if these naming make sense to native English speakers.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4935971,
      "reputation" : 303,
      "user_id" : 3974072,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b5faa5f92233942cebf571b4b84322d5?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Tim T",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3974072/tim-t"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1607925291,
    "creation_date" : 1607925291,
    "answer_id" : 65284245,
    "question_id" : 5322648,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>It should just be get{varname} like every other getter.  Changing it to &quot;is&quot; doesn't stop bad variable names, it just makes another unnecessary rule.</p>\n<p>Consider program generated code, or reflection derivations.</p>\n<p>It's a non-useful convention that should be dropped at the first available opportunity.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 3904494,
        "reputation" : 280,
        "user_id" : 3231510,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/Eq9Je.jpg?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Oscar Bravo",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3231510/oscar-bravo"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 1,
      "creation_date" : 1678890301,
      "post_id" : 69414543,
      "comment_id" : 133620911,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "Presumably, this is because if you <i>get</i> a Boolean, you may want to do something complicated with it, like <code>compareTo</code>, or <code>toString</code>. It would be a bit weird to say; <code>myThing.isWibble().toString()</code>. But if you get a boolean, all you can do is test it; <code>if (myThing.isWibble()) doWibble();</code>"
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 1665095,
        "reputation" : 576,
        "user_id" : 1532672,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d831264327d63f3c1994bca5104b2302?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "Christian Vermeulen",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1532672/christian-vermeulen"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1728980996,
      "post_id" : 69414543,
      "comment_id" : 139455806,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "I would argue you never use <code>boolean</code> but always use <code>Boolean</code> and always add both the <code>getCheck()</code> &#225;nd <code>isCheck()</code>. This gives you the most flexibility as the developer can choose wether he wants the entire <code>Boolean</code> for later processing, or you just quickly want to know wether it is true/false."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 15974771,
      "reputation" : 1071,
      "user_id" : 11527968,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/p5lgA.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Jimmy",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/11527968/jimmy"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 7,
    "last_activity_date" : 1678428378,
    "last_edit_date" : 1678428378,
    "creation_date" : 1633156110,
    "answer_id" : 69414543,
    "question_id" : 5322648,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>There is a markable point between <em><strong>setter/getter</strong></em> method of the data type <strong>Boolean</strong> and <strong>boolean</strong> in side a class ( for <em>pojo/entity</em>).</p>\n<ul>\n<li>For both Boolean and boolean the <em>setter</em> method should be <em><strong>setXXX()</strong></em> but <em>getter</em> method would be <em><strong>getXXX()</strong></em> and <em><strong>isXXX()</strong></em> respectively</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<p><strong>(a)</strong> if property is defines as <strong>Boolean</strong></p>\n<pre><code>private Boolean check;\n</code></pre>\n<p>the setter/getter method</p>\n<pre><code>public Boolean getCheck() {   // getXXX()\n    return check;\n}\n\npublic void setCheck(Boolean check) {\n    this.check = check;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p><strong>(b)</strong> if property is defines as <strong>boolean</strong></p>\n<pre><code>private boolean check;\n</code></pre>\n<p>the setter/getter method</p>\n<pre><code>   public boolean isCheck() {   // isXXX()\n        return check;\n    }\n    public void setCheck(boolean check) {\n        this.check = check;\n    }\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 24238330,
      "reputation" : 588,
      "user_id" : 18191094,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6562b04efea7bad8bb846bbc6f5cf5a1?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Henry S.",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/18191094/henry-s"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1654895901,
    "creation_date" : 1654895901,
    "answer_id" : 72579935,
    "question_id" : 5322648,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>It is highly recommended to use an <strong>adjective</strong> to name a boolean field. If you generate getter and setter using IntelliJ, you will find out that the getter is <code>isCurrent()</code> for both of boolean fields <code>current</code> and <code>isCurrent</code>.</p>\n<p>We can take a look at <a href=\"https://github.com/JetBrains/intellij-community/blob/master/plugins/lombok/testData/after/getter/GetterBoolean.java\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">IntelliJ community source code</a>, its test data shows that no matter whether your boolean field name starts with <code>is</code> or not, the name of getter starts with <code>is</code>.</p>\n<pre><code>class Getter {\n  boolean foo;\n  boolean isBar;\n  boolean hasBaz;\n\n  @java.lang.SuppressWarnings(&quot;all&quot;)\n  public boolean isFoo() {\n      return this.foo;\n  }\n\n  @java.lang.SuppressWarnings(&quot;all&quot;)\n  public boolean isBar() {\n      return this.isBar;\n  }\n\n  @java.lang.SuppressWarnings(&quot;all&quot;)\n  public boolean isHasBaz() {\n      return this.hasBaz;\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>It will be very confusing when you want to call the getter, when you boolean field name starts with <code>is</code>. Besides, when your colleagues want to get the value of a boolean field you defined, they will only know the getter' s name instead of the field' s name. In that case, the prefix <code>is</code> is not necessary.</p>\n<p>Here is another example, when I retrieve data from database to instantiate a object of Employee, the value of <code>isRetired</code> is always <code>false</code>. Because Java does not find an appropriate setter, the value of a boolean field is always default value, say <code>false</code>, which is not expected.</p>\n<pre><code>class Employee{\n    private int age;\n    private boolean isRetired;\n\n    ...\n    public boolean setRetired(boolean isRetired){\n        this.isRetired = isRetired;\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
